SIMPLE: umbrageous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: umbrageous
<hw>um*bra"geous</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧m*br⟦amac⟧"j⟦ucr⟧s; 277)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>ombrageux</ets> shy, skittish,
suspicious, in OF. also, shady. See <er>Umbrage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Forming or affording a shade; shady; shaded; <as>as,
<ex>umbrageous</ex> trees or foliage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Umbrageous</qex> grots and caves⟦br⟧
Of cool recess, o'er which the mantling vine⟦br⟧
Lays forth her purple grape.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not easily perceived, as if from being darkened or
shaded; obscure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir H.
Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Feeling jealousy or umbrage; taking, or disposed to
take, umbrage; suspicious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Bp.
Warburton.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Um*bra"geous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos>
-- <wf>Um*bra"geous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Umbrate</ent>⟦br⟧
